T1  - Do Physiological and Spiritual Factors Affect Economic Decisions?
AU  - DEMIROGLU, CEM
AU  - OZBAS, OGUZHAN
AU  - SILVA, RUI C.
AU  - ULU, MEHMET FATİH
Y1  - 2021/10/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13032
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2481
EP  - 2523
VL  - 76
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13032
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We examine the effects of physiology and spiritual sentiment on economic decision-making in the context of Ramadan, an entire lunar month of daily fasting and increased spiritual reflection in the Muslim faith. Using an administrative data set of bank loans originated in Turkey during 2003 to 2013, we find that small business loans originated during Ramadan are 15% more likely to default within two years of origination. Loans originated in hot Ramadans, when adverse physiological effects of fasting are greatest, and those approved by the busiest bank branches perform worse. Despite their worse performance, Ramadan loans have lower credit spreads.
ER  - 

