T1  - Structuring Mortgages for Macroeconomic Stability
AU  - CAMPBELL, JOHN Y.
AU  - CLARA, NUNO
AU  - COCCO, JOÃO F.
Y1  - 2021/10/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/10/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13056
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2525
EP  - 2576
VL  - 76
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13056
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We study mortgage design features aimed at stabilizing the macroeconomy. We model overlapping generations of borrowers and an infinitely lived risk-averse representative lender. Mortgages are priced using an equilibrium pricing kernel derived from the lender's endogenous consumption. We consider an adjustable-rate mortgage with an option that during recessions allows borrowers to pay only interest on their loan and extend its maturity. The option stabilizes consumption growth over the business cycle, shifts defaults to expansions, and enhances welfare. The cyclical properties of the contract are attractive to a risk-averse lender so that the mortgage can be provided at a relatively low cost.
ER  - 

